WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.560
Welcome back after lunch. It's been a great conference so far. It's been great to be here.

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:16.920
My name is David Smith. I'm a cloud advocate with Microsoft. So basically that means I'm

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:20.639
Microsoft's connection with the R community. So if there's anything you would like me to

00:00:20.639 --> 00:00:24.040
communicate back to the development teams back in Redmond, just have a chat with me

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:31.760
and I'll pass that on. But today I would like to talk to you about machine learning operations.

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:37.360
And that's the process of efficiently and reliably building machine learning models

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:43.080
at scale. We call it MLOps. It's a relatively new term. You might see it being related to

00:00:43.080 --> 00:00:47.320
something you're more familiar with, which is DevOps. And DevOps itself, I don't have

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:51.880
time to get into all the details of that, but a definition that I like, which comes

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:58.119
from one of my colleagues at Microsoft, is that DevOps is the union of people, process

00:00:58.119 --> 00:01:04.400
and products to enable the continuous delivery of value to your end users. And note that

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:08.279
word value there. We're not talking about software. We're not talking about applications.

00:01:08.279 --> 00:01:11.919
We're talking about value in general. So it seems like it's something that we could also

00:01:11.919 --> 00:01:17.400
apply to machine learning in the same way that it's traditionally applied to regular

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:23.720
applications. So what DevOps gives us is a nice process for delivering applications

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:30.120
in general. We plan, we develop and test those applications, we release them to production.

00:01:30.120 --> 00:01:33.320
And once they're in production, we're not done because in production we monitor and

00:01:33.320 --> 00:01:38.160
learn from our users' experiences with those applications and go through that entire cycle

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:45.760
again. And so the question that I want to ask here is, can we apply a similar process

00:01:45.760 --> 00:01:52.160
to DevOps for building applications to building machine learning models with R in particular

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:56.839
in this case? And I don't know about you, but at least in my experience when working

00:01:56.839 --> 00:02:01.639
with machine learning models, it's a little bit different than building applications with

00:02:01.639 --> 00:02:07.639
regular programming languages. You start with some data, you might try a model, you might

00:02:07.639 --> 00:02:12.479
try another model, you'll evaluate the results, you'll decide that you might need some more

00:02:12.479 --> 00:02:18.839
data, you might need a different model. It's a very iterative process. But at the end of

00:02:18.839 --> 00:02:24.039
that process, what you get is a model that you'd like to put into production and you

00:02:24.039 --> 00:02:27.960
throw it over the wall to the engineering team to do something with it. At least that

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:32.399
was my experience up until relatively recently. I don't know if it was yours as well. But

00:02:32.399 --> 00:02:38.080
you can see that this is kind of very different to the modern way of building applications

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:43.720
with continuous integration and continuous delivery. So can we get to that stage with

00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:49.440
machine learning? And I think one of the ways that we can think about that is to have a

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:55.399
look at some of the differences between traditional development processes, DevOps, and machine

00:02:55.399 --> 00:03:02.199
learning building, MLOps. Now in both cases, we're working with files, you know, that source

00:03:02.199 --> 00:03:07.440
code. You know, it might be C++ or .NET files on the regular application side of things.

00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:12.679
But with machine learning, we're also working with other artifacts, things like data files.

00:03:12.679 --> 00:03:18.080
There's a whole thread I could go down to get down in at this point about thinking about

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:24.759
what does it mean to have a 55 megabyte data file that you're analyzing and putting that

00:03:24.759 --> 00:03:31.440
into Git? Short hashtag don't do that. But lots of issues around managing data that don't

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:36.639
come up in traditional development processes. Same things if you're working with notebooks

00:03:36.639 --> 00:03:41.559
or RMD documents or R Markdown documents. How do we deal with those and how do they

00:03:41.559 --> 00:03:49.080
manage in source code control systems? A good practice when building applications is rather

00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:54.000
than managing infrastructure directly by pointing and clicking in consoles and terminals is

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:59.119
to manage that infrastructure with commands in code. And those same principles apply on

00:03:59.119 --> 00:04:03.679
the machine learning side as well, with an additional wrinkle that we often have to manage

00:04:03.679 --> 00:04:10.839
environments. Think for in the R case, managing the packages and the package versions that

00:04:10.839 --> 00:04:16.200
need to exist for your R model to run in a reliable fashion. So we want to be able to

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:21.760
manage those as code as well. I touched a little bit about those issues of working with

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:27.359
source code control systems. Those also apply in the machine learning operations scenario.

00:04:27.359 --> 00:04:32.399
But there are other things we need to track changes in as well, not just the source code.

00:04:32.399 --> 00:04:38.640
We also want to track changes in our experiments. And by that I mean, as we try out different

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:42.959
types of models, perhaps different transformations of our data, we're looking for some kind of

00:04:42.959 --> 00:04:48.160
outcome, perhaps the model with the best accuracy. And we'd like to be able to track that as

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:54.399
well in a reproducible way so that we can always go back to prior experiments if we

00:04:54.399 --> 00:04:59.359
end up using that one instead. And I've mentioned already this issue about managing data sets

00:04:59.359 --> 00:05:05.679
and source code. When we're building applications in a DevOps environment, typically we're building

00:05:05.679 --> 00:05:12.880
binary executables. Those builds might take minutes, maybe hours. That's kind of the typical

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:17.760
limit for most types of applications. You're typically building on sort of commodity computing

00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:22.959
infrastructure. But on the machine learning side, rather than building, in addition to

00:05:22.959 --> 00:05:26.640
building executables rather, we're building the models, we're training the models that

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:32.239
become part of those executables. And that model training, especially in sort of deep

00:05:32.239 --> 00:05:38.959
learning type of environments, could likely take hours, might well take days. I've seen

00:05:38.959 --> 00:05:44.320
examples where model training takes months. And so how do we put that into a traditional

00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:49.440
DevOps type of environment? And also how do we incorporate the exotic computing environments

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:55.040
like the GPU computing environments that we need for deep learning? When it comes to version

00:05:55.040 --> 00:06:00.239
control, version management, when we're building applications, we like to give versions to the

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:06.799
applications that we build and release. On the machine learning side, we would like to assign

00:06:06.799 --> 00:06:12.320
versions to models so we can track when we change a model and then go back to the underlying data

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:20.880
and code that created that model and do so reproducibly. And another sort of side branch

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:26.720
that I could go into for hours is this whole concept of tests when it comes to machine learning

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:32.640
as opposed to developing applications. On the application side, tests are fairly deterministic.

00:06:32.640 --> 00:06:37.119
Did it break? Did it cause an error? Did it give the right response? But in machine learning,

00:06:37.119 --> 00:06:42.239
tests tend to be a little more probabilistic. You know, think of the question of, is this a

00:06:42.239 --> 00:06:47.119
picture of a cat? That's not so much of a yes or a no type question. It's more of a probabilistic

00:06:47.119 --> 00:06:51.920
thing that we need to determine. And so the way we do testing is different. I can't go into all of

00:06:51.920 --> 00:06:55.679
these topics today, but I'm just going to touch on a few of them. But I just wanted to give you this

00:06:55.679 --> 00:06:59.679
as just an illustration that there are quite a few differences, in my opinion,

00:06:59.679 --> 00:07:04.160
between machine learning operations and traditional DevOps. And we need to incorporate

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:09.200
those differences into any process that we're using when we build applications with machine learning.

